data.content:
Yes — use the generic `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()`, which asserts the type **and** returns the cast object so you can inspect it further:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

This gives you a clear failure message (e.g. *"Expected type: EmailHandler, Actual type: SmsHandler"*) instead of an `InvalidCastException`. The generic overload (MSTest v3+) both asserts and returns the typed value in one call.
